💥 What interviewers/judges will like

If you say:

“We integrated external monitoring via webhooks instead of reinventing monitoring infra”

What UptimeRobot actually tells you

When it sends a webhook, the data is usually like:

{
  "alertType": "DOWN",
  "monitorName": "API Server",
  "url": "https://api.client.com",
  "timestamp": "..."
}

So you get:

WHICH monitor failed (API, Website, etc.)
WHEN it failed
WHAT URL failed
❌ What it does NOT tell you

It will NOT say:

“Database crashed”
“Memory leak”
“Server overloaded”
“Bug in code”

Because it’s just doing this:

Request → No response → = DOWN

That’s it.

🧠 Then how do real systems know the issue?

This is where your platform becomes valuable

You combine 3 things:

1. Monitor Name (VERY IMPORTANT)

Instead of naming it:

❌ "Monitor 1"

You name it smartly:

"API - Production"
"Payments Service"
"Auth Server"

So when webhook comes:

"Payments Service is DOWN"

👉 Now you already know the area of failure

2. Human Updates (War Room)

Engineer says:

"Investigating DB connection pool"

Another says:

"High CPU usage on payment service"

👉 This is the real root cause discovery

3. AI (your bonus feature)

You can take:

monitor name
recent logs (optional)
timeline messages

And generate:

"Possible cause: database connection exhaustion"
🔥 So your system flow becomes:
UptimeRobot → "API is DOWN"
                ↓
Your system → creates incident
                ↓
War Room → humans investigate
                ↓
Updates → timeline builds story
                ↓
AI → suggests root cause
💡 How YOU should design the incident title

When webhook comes, don’t just say:

❌ “Site Down”

Instead:

title = `${payload.monitorName} is DOWN`

Example:

"Payments Service is DOWN"
🧠 Make it smarter (pro touch)

You can map monitor → service:

{
  "api.client.com": "API Service",
  "pay.client.com": "Payments"
}

So your incident becomes:

"Payments Service Outage"
⚡ Real-world comparison

Think like this:

UptimeRobot = Fire alarm
Your platform = Fire control room

Fire alarm says:

“There’s smoke in the kitchen”

It does NOT say:

“Oil caught fire due to overheating”

That’s for humans (and maybe AI) to figure out.

💥 What judges want to see

If you explain it like this:

“We use external monitoring for detection, but root cause is derived from human collaboration and AI-assisted analysis”

→ That’s 🔥 strong answer

